& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Noncirrhotic portal hypertension (NCPH) is an uncommon but important entity caused by impaired flow dynamics in the portal venous system in the absence of advanced fibrosis. The exact prevalence of this disease is unknown since many patients with NCPH are labeled as having cryptogenic cirrhosis. Numerous disease processes performed with different mechanisms can result in this entity. Based on the anatomic level of impairment of portal flow, NCPH is classified into prehepatic, intrahepatic, and posthepatic forms. The exact pathophysiology in many cases of intrahepatic NCPH is not well known, and there are overlapping terminologies used to describe histopathologic changes in the liver. The clinical and imaging findings are heterogeneous and are influenced by the mechanism and the underlying cause. In particular, patterns of portal hypertension and liver morphology are different among pre-, intra-, and posthepatic forms. All causes of NCPH can result in liver dysmorphism, but these changes are more drastic with intrahepatic and posthepatic forms (especially when associated with nodular regenerative hyperplasia) and can occasionally mimic cirrhosis. Prehepatic NCPH classically results in marked splenomegaly and large collateral formation with no ascites. On the other hand, ascites is the most common sign in posthepatic NCPH. Venographic pressure measurement and liver biopsy are required for definitive diagnosis. The authors review the current understanding of the mechanisms and causes of NCPH and discuss the approach to imaging findings, role of elastography, management, and complications.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2025</div><div role="paragraph">Supplemental material is available for this article.</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/large/rg.240210.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240210">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.240210">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="Mechanisms of increased pressure in the portal venous system. Major pathways are increased flow with or without vasoconstriction of veins and venules, intraluminal occlusion, extrinsic compression of intrahepatic veins and venules, and deformity and narrowing of sinusoids. Ca = calcium, ext = external, int = internal, Na = sodium, tra = transmural."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig1.jpg" height="1765" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Mechanisms of increased pressure in the portal venous system. Major pathways are increased flow with or without vasoconstriction of veins and venules, intraluminal occlusion, extrinsic compression of intrahepatic veins and venules, and deformity and narrowing of sinusoids. <i>Ca</i> = calcium, <i>ext</i> = external, <i>int</i> = internal, <i>Na</i> = sodium, <i>tra</i> = transmural.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="EPVO in a 61-year-old woman with a remote history of splenectomy (for lymphoma) complicated by splenic venous thrombosis. (A) Coronal maximum intensity projection postcontrast CT image shows chronic occlusion of the portal vein with cavernous transformation (circle). (B) Axial postcontrast CT image shows abnormal liver morphology (although not cirrhotic), with enlargement of caudate and left lobe and with atrophy of the right posterior segment. No ascites was present. There was no evidence of significant fibrosis or other parenchymal abnormalities at liver biopsy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig2.jpg" height="1333" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. EPVO in a 61-year-old woman with a remote history of splenectomy (for lymphoma) complicated by splenic venous thrombosis. <b>(A)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection postcontrast CT image shows chronic occlusion of the portal vein with cavernous transformation (circle). <b>(B)</b> Axial postcontrast CT image shows abnormal liver morphology (although not cirrhotic), with enlargement of caudate and left lobe and with atrophy of the right posterior segment. No ascites was present. There was no evidence of significant fibrosis or other parenchymal abnormalities at liver biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Abernethy malformation in a 3.5-year-old boy. (A) Coronal contrast-enhanced MR venogram shows the absence of intrahepatic branches of the portal vein and a large shunt (arrow) between the extrahepatic portal vein (*) and IVC. (B) Axial postcontrast CT image obtained during the venous phase better shows the large end-to-side shunt between the extrahepatic portal vein and IVC (arrows), consistent with a type Ib Abernethy malformation. Abernethy malformation is a rare congenital form of portosystemic shunts due to the presence of embryonic vessels. All or a majority of flow from the splenic and mesenteric veins is shunted into systemic circulations (usually the IVC). The portal veins are aplastic or hypoplastic. pHTN is an uncommon complication of Abernethy malformation given the large extrahepatic portosystemic communication but occasionally can be seen when the congenital shunt is small."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig3.jpg" height="882" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. Abernethy malformation in a 3.5-year-old boy. <b>(A)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced MR venogram shows the absence of intrahepatic branches of the portal vein and a large shunt (arrow) between the extrahepatic portal vein (*) and IVC. <b>(B)</b> Axial postcontrast CT image obtained during the venous phase better shows the large end-to-side shunt between the extrahepatic portal vein and IVC (arrows), consistent with a type Ib Abernethy malformation. Abernethy malformation is a rare congenital form of portosystemic shunts due to the presence of embryonic vessels. All or a majority of flow from the splenic and mesenteric veins is shunted into systemic circulations (usually the IVC). The portal veins are aplastic or hypoplastic. pHTN is an uncommon complication of Abernethy malformation given the large extrahepatic portosystemic communication but occasionally can be seen when the congenital shunt is small.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Massive splenomegaly in a 62-year-old man with a history of polycythemia vera. Coronal postcontrast CT image shows massive splenomegaly and extensive upper abdominal venous collaterals. Portal and splenic veins were widely patent, and there was no ascites present. Note the absence of cirrhotic features."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig4.jpg" height="841" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Massive splenomegaly in a 62-year-old man with a history of polycythemia vera. Coronal postcontrast CT image shows massive splenomegaly and extensive upper abdominal venous collaterals. Portal and splenic veins were widely patent, and there was no ascites present. Note the absence of cirrhotic features.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Schistosomiasis in three patients. (A) Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained during the equilibrium phase in a 19-year-old man with a clinical and laboratory diagnosis of schistosomiasis shows bandlike areas of periportal enhancement (arrows) likely due to a periportal granulomatous response and fibrosis. (B) Axial noncontrast CT image in a 73-year-old woman shows calcified septa (arrows), referred to as a turtle back sign, that are considered pathognomonic for hepatic schistosomiasis. (C) Axial postcontrast CT image in a 74-year-old woman with a clinical and laboratory diagnosis of schistosomiasis shows extension of hilar fat to the intrahepatic perivascular space (arrows), presumably due to fibrosis-related volume loss. Note the absence of ascites in these patients."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig5.jpg" height="1875" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Schistosomiasis in three patients. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image obtained during the equilibrium phase in a 19-year-old man with a clinical and laboratory diagnosis of schistosomiasis shows bandlike areas of periportal enhancement (arrows) likely due to a periportal granulomatous response and fibrosis. <b>(B)</b> Axial noncontrast CT image in a 73-year-old woman shows calcified septa (arrows), referred to as a turtle back sign, that are considered pathognomonic for hepatic schistosomiasis. <b>(C)</b> Axial postcontrast CT image in a 74-year-old woman with a clinical and laboratory diagnosis of schistosomiasis shows extension of hilar fat to the intrahepatic perivascular space (arrows), presumably due to fibrosis-related volume loss. Note the absence of ascites in these patients.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="IPH in a 47-year-old woman who presented with pHTN. (A, B) Axial postcontrast CT images show a markedly dysmorphic liver (central hypertrophy, peripheral atrophy, and no surface nodularity in A), splenomegaly (B), and numerous collateral vessels. Free hepatic venous pressure (FHVP), wedged hepatic venous pressure (WHVP), and right atrium pressure were 8, 14, and 6 mm Hg, respectively, with a calculated hepatic venous pressure gradient of 6 mm Hg, which was elevated and suggestive of the intrahepatic level of portal flow impairment. Liver biopsy showed hepatoportal sclerosis without significant fibrosis, compatible with portosinusoidal vascular disease (also known as IPH). (C) Axial CT image shows numerous phleboliths in the colonic wall, note also those in the gastric wall in B, which is a rare complication of long-standing pHTN and is mostly reported with NCPH."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig6.jpg" height="2133" width="852" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. IPH in a 47-year-old woman who presented with pHTN. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial postcontrast CT images show a markedly dysmorphic liver (central hypertrophy, peripheral atrophy, and no surface nodularity in <b>A</b>), splenomegaly <b>(B)</b>, and numerous collateral vessels. Free hepatic venous pressure (FHVP), wedged hepatic venous pressure (WHVP), and right atrium pressure were 8, 14, and 6 mm Hg, respectively, with a calculated hepatic venous pressure gradient of 6 mm Hg, which was elevated and suggestive of the intrahepatic level of portal flow impairment. Liver biopsy showed hepatoportal sclerosis without significant fibrosis, compatible with portosinusoidal vascular disease (also known as IPH). <b>(C)</b> Axial CT image shows numerous phleboliths in the colonic wall, note also those in the gastric wall in <b>B</b>, which is a rare complication of long-standing pHTN and is mostly reported with NCPH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="Pathogenesis of NRH. Occlusion or narrowing of portal and hepatic venules and sinusoids (due to intraluminal causes or extrinsic compression) and congestion result in arterialization of the liver and changes in the level of oxygen and nutrients, which in turn result in nodular regeneration. A separate proposed mechanism is venopathy and endothelial injury to sinusoids and portal venules."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig7.jpg" height="1241" width="1746" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. Pathogenesis of NRH. Occlusion or narrowing of portal and hepatic venules and sinusoids (due to intraluminal causes or extrinsic compression) and congestion result in arterialization of the liver and changes in the level of oxygen and nutrients, which in turn result in nodular regeneration. A separate proposed mechanism is venopathy and endothelial injury to sinusoids and portal venules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="NRH in a 61-year-old woman with a history of unexplained splenomegaly. (A) Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows noncirrhotic liver morphology. The patient had a history of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy and multiple myeloma in remission. (B) Axial MR elastogram shows elevated liver stiffness (4.3 kPa) suggestive of advanced fibrosis (F3–F4). Liver biopsy showed moderate NRH changes and portal venopathy, with only mild portal and perivenular fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig8.jpg" height="1486" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. NRH in a 61-year-old woman with a history of unexplained splenomegaly. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows noncirrhotic liver morphology. The patient had a history of chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy and multiple myeloma in remission. <b>(B)</b> Axial MR elastogram shows elevated liver stiffness (4.3 kPa) suggestive of advanced fibrosis (F3–F4). Liver biopsy showed moderate NRH changes and portal venopathy, with only mild portal and perivenular fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="NRH in a 24-year-old man with a history of cystic fibrosis. (A) Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows cirrhotic liver morphology with splenomegaly, ascites, and collateral vessels. (B) Photograph of a gross specimen of the liver explant shows a nodular liver. Histopathologic examination of the liver specimen showed moderate NRH, as well as incomplete bridging fibrosis (incomplete cirrhosis) with biliary features. Nodularity of the liver and pHTN were likely due to a combination of advanced fibrosis and NRH in this patient."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig9.jpg" height="658" width="1766" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. NRH in a 24-year-old man with a history of cystic fibrosis. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows cirrhotic liver morphology with splenomegaly, ascites, and collateral vessels. <b>(B)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen of the liver explant shows a nodular liver. Histopathologic examination of the liver specimen showed moderate NRH, as well as incomplete bridging fibrosis (incomplete cirrhosis) with biliary features. Nodularity of the liver and pHTN were likely due to a combination of advanced fibrosis and NRH in this patient.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man with a history of systemic amyloidosis. (A) Axial T2-weighted MR image shows splenomegaly. (B) Axial MR elastogram shows elevated liver stiffness measurement (LSM) suggestive of advanced fibrosis. (C, D) Photomicrograph from a subsequent transjugular biopsy shows eosinophilic, hyaline, and acellular material involving the sinusoids, portal triads, and vasculature (oval in C), which were positive for Congo red staining (D). (Hematoxylin-eosin stain [C]; original magnification, ×10 [C] and ×20 [D].)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig10.jpg" height="1289" width="1653" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Amyloidosis in a 63-year-old man with a history of systemic amyloidosis. <b>(A)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows splenomegaly. <b>(B)</b> Axial MR elastogram shows elevated liver stiffness measurement (LSM) suggestive of advanced fibrosis. <b>(C, D)</b> Photomicrograph from a subsequent transjugular biopsy shows eosinophilic, hyaline, and acellular material involving the sinusoids, portal triads, and vasculature (oval in <b>C</b>), which were positive for Congo red staining <b>(D)</b>. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain [<b>C</b>]; original magnification, ×10 [<b>C</b>] and ×20 [<b>D</b>].)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome in a 36-year-old man with a history of liver transplant who presented with decompensation and progressive pHTN. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted (A) and T2-weighted (B) MR images show abnormal liver morphology with markedly heterogeneous enhancement and heterogeneous T2 signal intensity. Biopsy was consistent with sinusoidal obstruction syndrome, without evidence of significant fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig11.jpg" height="611" width="1798" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome in a 36-year-old man with a history of liver transplant who presented with decompensation and progressive pHTN. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted <b>(A)</b> and T2-weighted <b>(B)</b> MR images show abnormal liver morphology with markedly heterogeneous enhancement and heterogeneous T2 signal intensity. Biopsy was consistent with sinusoidal obstruction syndrome, without evidence of significant fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="BCS in a 45-year-old man who presented with new-onset hepatic failure and findings of pHTN. (A) Axial postcontrast CT image shows heterogeneous enhancement of liver with nonvisualization of hepatic veins. Note the paraesophageal varices (arrow). (B) Subsequent catheter cavogram further confirms nonvisualization and occlusion of all hepatic veins, consistent with BCS."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig12.jpg" height="541" width="1700" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. BCS in a 45-year-old man who presented with new-onset hepatic failure and findings of pHTN. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast CT image shows heterogeneous enhancement of liver with nonvisualization of hepatic veins. Note the paraesophageal varices (arrow). <b>(B)</b> Subsequent catheter cavogram further confirms nonvisualization and occlusion of all hepatic veins, consistent with BCS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="IVC stenosis in a 45-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematous. (A, B) Axial (A) and coronal (B) postcontrast CT images show pHTN with splenomegaly, recanalization of the paraumbilical vein, and ascites. (C) Catheter cavogram further confirms the narrowing of intrahepatic IVC at the level of hepatic veins (arrows in B and C). FHVP, WHVP, and right atrial pressure were 13, 18, and 3 mm Hg, respectively, with a calculated hepatic venous pressure gradient of 5 mm Hg. Liver biopsy showed sinusoidal dilatation with minimal periportal fibrosis (stage 0–1)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig13.jpg" height="738" width="2247" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. IVC stenosis in a 45-year-old woman with a history of systemic lupus erythematous. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and coronal <b>(B)</b> postcontrast CT images show pHTN with splenomegaly, recanalization of the paraumbilical vein, and ascites. <b>(C)</b> Catheter cavogram further confirms the narrowing of intrahepatic IVC at the level of hepatic veins (arrows in <b>B</b> and <b>C</b>). FHVP, WHVP, and right atrial pressure were 13, 18, and 3 mm Hg, respectively, with a calculated hepatic venous pressure gradient of 5 mm Hg. Liver biopsy showed sinusoidal dilatation with minimal periportal fibrosis (stage 0–1).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic" aria-label="Cardiomyopathy in a 30-year-old woman with a history of dilated cardiomyopathy (no history of chronic liver disease). (A) Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a dysmorphic liver (nodular surface and enlarged caudate lobe) with ascites, suggestive of pHTN. (B) Coronal maximum intensity projection postcontrast CT pulmonary angiogram shows cardiomegaly with reflux of contrast agent into the hepatic veins (arrow), consistent with right-sided heart failure. The patient underwent liver biopsy in preparation for a heart transplant, which did not show significant fibrosis. In patients with congestive hepatopathy, the detection of advanced fibrosis based on liver morphology is challenging. Surface nodularity in this setting has low specificity for advanced fibrosis and can be attributed to NRH."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig14.jpg" height="678" width="1750" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Cardiomyopathy in a 30-year-old woman with a history of dilated cardiomyopathy (no history of chronic liver disease). <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a dysmorphic liver (nodular surface and enlarged caudate lobe) with ascites, suggestive of pHTN. <b>(B)</b> Coronal maximum intensity projection postcontrast CT pulmonary angiogram shows cardiomegaly with reflux of contrast agent into the hepatic veins (arrow), consistent with right-sided heart failure. The patient underwent liver biopsy in preparation for a heart transplant, which did not show significant fibrosis. In patients with congestive hepatopathy, the detection of advanced fibrosis based on liver morphology is challenging. Surface nodularity in this setting has low specificity for advanced fibrosis and can be attributed to NRH.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic" aria-label="Fontan-associated liver disease in a 37-year-old man with a history of single ventricle and Fontan procedure. Axial postcontrast CT image shows a dysmorphic liver with abnormal liver contours. The patient also had splenomegaly (not shown). Biopsy showed sinusoidal dilatation without evidence of significant fibrosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig15.jpg" height="513" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Fontan-associated liver disease in a 37-year-old man with a history of single ventricle and Fontan procedure. Axial postcontrast CT image shows a dysmorphic liver with abnormal liver contours. The patient also had splenomegaly (not shown). Biopsy showed sinusoidal dilatation without evidence of significant fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic" aria-label="Proposed approach for the assessment of patients with pHTN. *Many patients with NCPH have an atypical pattern of pHTN defined as the absence of ascites, or trace ascites, despite marked splenomegaly and collateral formation. Splenomegaly and collateral vessels out of proportion to the severity of chronic liver disease (CLD) should also be considered as an atypical pattern."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig16.jpg" height="1037" width="2250" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Proposed approach for the assessment of patients with pHTN. *Many patients with NCPH have an atypical pattern of pHTN defined as the absence of ascites, or trace ascites, despite marked splenomegaly and collateral formation. Splenomegaly and collateral vessels out of proportion to the severity of chronic liver disease <i>(CLD)</i> should also be considered as an atypical pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic" aria-label="Masslike cavernoma in a 48-year-old man with a history of JAK2 mutation and extrahepatic portal vein obstruction and resultant NCPH. (A, B) Axial T2-weighted (A) and postcontrast T1-weighted (B) MR images show a hilar mass with progressive enhancement (circle). (C) Doppler US image of this structure shows numerous collateral vessels with nonphasic flow and nonvisualization of the main portal vein (MPV). (D) Axial T2-weighted MR image at a higher level shows mild dilatation of intrahepatic bile ducts with abrupt narrowing at the level of hilum, suggestive of portal biliopathy (also known as portal cholangiopathy)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig17.jpg" height="1301" width="1677" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Masslike cavernoma in a 48-year-old man with a history of <i>JAK2</i> mutation and extrahepatic portal vein obstruction and resultant NCPH. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial T2-weighted <b>(A)</b> and postcontrast T1-weighted <b>(B)</b> MR images show a hilar mass with progressive enhancement (circle). <b>(C)</b> Doppler US image of this structure shows numerous collateral vessels with nonphasic flow and nonvisualization of the main portal vein <i>(MPV)</i>. <b>(D)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image at a higher level shows mild dilatation of intrahepatic bile ducts with abrupt narrowing at the level of hilum, suggestive of portal biliopathy (also known as portal cholangiopathy).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic" aria-label="FNH-like nodule in a 42-year-old woman with a remote history of colorectal cancer. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images obtained during the arterial phase (A) and with a 20-minute delay after administration of hepatobiliary contrast agent (B) show an arterially hyperenhancing lesion in the left lateral segment (arrow), with retention of contrast agent in the delayed hepatobiliary phase. The patient had undergone a chemotherapy regimen that contained oxaliplatin. Targeted biopsy showed an FNH-like lesion and sinusoidal dilatation in the background liver. Note the splenomegaly and heterogeneous enhancement of the liver due to sinusoidal dilatation (a known complication of oxaliplatin)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig18.jpg" height="597" width="1699" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. FNH-like nodule in a 42-year-old woman with a remote history of colorectal cancer. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR images obtained during the arterial phase <b>(A)</b> and with a 20-minute delay after administration of hepatobiliary contrast agent <b>(B)</b> show an arterially hyperenhancing lesion in the left lateral segment (arrow), with retention of contrast agent in the delayed hepatobiliary phase. The patient had undergone a chemotherapy regimen that contained oxaliplatin. Targeted biopsy showed an FNH-like lesion and sinusoidal dilatation in the background liver. Note the splenomegaly and heterogeneous enhancement of the liver due to sinusoidal dilatation (a known complication of oxaliplatin).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven hepatoportal sclerosis (also known as portosinusoidal vascular disorder) causing NCPH in a 59-year-old woman. (A) Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a dysmorphic (although noncirrhotic) liver with relative enlargement of the left lateral segment and atrophy of the left medial segment. Also note the splenomegaly and collateral vessels (arrows). (B) Axial MR elastogram shows mildly elevated mean liver stiffness (3.2 kPa) and elevated mean spleen stiffness (13.9 kPa). * = spleen."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig19.jpg" height="686" width="1848" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Biopsy-proven hepatoportal sclerosis (also known as portosinusoidal vascular disorder) causing NCPH in a 59-year-old woman. <b>(A)</b> Axial postcontrast T1-weighted MR image shows a dysmorphic (although noncirrhotic) liver with relative enlargement of the left lateral segment and atrophy of the left medial segment. Also note the splenomegaly and collateral vessels (arrows). <b>(B)</b> Axial MR elastogram shows mildly elevated mean liver stiffness (3.2 kPa) and elevated mean spleen stiffness (13.9 kPa). * = spleen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic" aria-label="Venographic pressure measurement. (A) Native frontal projection intraprocedural fluoroscopic image from a hepatic venogram shows opacification of right hepatic vein (arrow), confirming the patency and anatomy of this vein in preparation for pressure measurement. (B) Subsequent fluoroscopic image shows positioning of the catheter in the distal right hepatic vein, near the confluence of hepatic veins, for measurement of FHVP. (C) Final fluoroscopic image shows balloon occlusion (arrow) of the proximal aspect of the right hepatic vein (near the venules), with opacification of hepatic venules in preparation for measurement of WHVP."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig20.jpg" height="711" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Venographic pressure measurement. <b>(A)</b> Native frontal projection intraprocedural fluoroscopic image from a hepatic venogram shows opacification of right hepatic vein (arrow), confirming the patency and anatomy of this vein in preparation for pressure measurement. <b>(B)</b> Subsequent fluoroscopic image shows positioning of the catheter in the distal right hepatic vein, near the confluence of hepatic veins, for measurement of FHVP. <b>(C)</b> Final fluoroscopic image shows balloon occlusion (arrow) of the proximal aspect of the right hepatic vein (near the venules), with opacification of hepatic venules in preparation for measurement of WHVP.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic" aria-label="Large rectal varices in a 47-year-old man with a long-standing history of extrahepatic portal vein occlusion (likely as a complication from a bout of omphalitis in childhood) and intermittent rectal bleeding since childhood. (A, B) Axial (A) and coronal (B) postcontrast CT images show marked rectosigmoid wall thickening (arrows) and phleboliths. The patient underwent sigmoid colectomy. (C) Photograph of the gross specimen and histopathologic examination findings (not shown) show prominent and diffuse submucosal and subserosal venous dilatation with muscularization of veins, consistent with impaired venous drainage as a complication of long-standing portal vein thrombosis."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig21.jpg" height="1126" width="1503" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span>. Large rectal varices in a 47-year-old man with a long-standing history of extrahepatic portal vein occlusion (likely as a complication from a bout of omphalitis in childhood) and intermittent rectal bleeding since childhood. <b>(A, B)</b> Axial <b>(A)</b> and coronal <b>(B)</b> postcontrast CT images show marked rectosigmoid wall thickening (arrows) and phleboliths. The patient underwent sigmoid colectomy. <b>(C)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen and histopathologic examination findings (not shown) show prominent and diffuse submucosal and subserosal venous dilatation with muscularization of veins, consistent with impaired venous drainage as a complication of long-standing portal vein thrombosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic" aria-label="Portal vein thrombosis in a 40-year-old man with a history of cystic fibrosis trait and chronic pancreatitis. (A) Coronal postcontrast CT image shows chronic portomesenteric thrombosis with associated collateral formation. (B) Frontal projection venogram from the patent portion of the superior mesenteric vein shows the cavernous transformation. (C) Frontal projection venogram obtained after direct percutaneous puncture of the splenic vein shows occlusion of the distal splenic vein and portal confluence. (D) Frontal projection venogram shows venous recanalization and a transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.240210/asset/images/rg.240210.fig22.jpg" height="1195" width="2002" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Portal vein thrombosis in a 40-year-old man with a history of cystic fibrosis trait and chronic pancreatitis. <b>(A)</b> Coronal postcontrast CT image shows chronic portomesenteric thrombosis with associated collateral formation. <b>(B)</b> Frontal projection venogram from the patent portion of the superior mesenteric vein shows the cavernous transformation. <b>(C)</b> Frontal projection venogram obtained after direct percutaneous puncture of the splenic vein shows occlusion of the distal splenic vein and portal confluence. <b>(D)</b> Frontal projection venogram shows venous recanalization and a transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.240210&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Sanyal AJ, Bosch J, Blei A, Arroyo V. Portal hypertension and its complications. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2008;134(6):1715–1728.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2008.03.007">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18471549/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Portal+hypertension+and+its+complications&amp;author=AJ+Sanyal&amp;author=J+Bosch&amp;author=A+Blei&amp;author=V+Arroyo&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=1715-1728&amp;doi=10.1053%2Fj.gastro.2008.03.007&amp;pmid=18471549">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">García-Pagán JC, Gracia-Sancho J, Bosch J. Functional aspects on the pathophysiology of portal hypertension in cirrhosis. <em>J Hepatol</em> 2012;57(2):458–461.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jhep.2012.03.007">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22504334/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Functional+aspects+on+the+pathophysiology+of+portal+hypertension+in+cirrhosis&amp;author=JC+Garc%C3%ADa-Pag%C3%A1n&amp;author=J+Gracia-Sancho&amp;author=J+Bosch&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=J+Hepatol&amp;pages=458-461&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.jhep.2012.03.007&amp;pmid=22504334">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gunarathne LS, Rajapaksha H, Shackel N, Angus PW, Herath CB. Cirrhotic portal hypertension: From pathophysiology to novel therapeutics. <em>World J Gastroenterol</em> 2020;26(40):6111–6140.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.3748/wjg.v26.i40.6111">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33177789/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Cirrhotic+portal+hypertension%3A+From+pathophysiology+to+novel+therapeutics&amp;author=LS+Gunarathne&amp;author=H+Rajapaksha&amp;author=N+Shackel&amp;author